    "# **Quick Start Guide**\n",
    "\n",
    "This Quick Start guide provides an overview of DPM Tools and highlights some of its main functionality.\n",
    "\n",
    "## **Objectives**\n",
    "The primary objectives of this project is to provide users with a unified interface for processing, analyzing, and visualizing digital porous media images. We aim to complement other existing software tools that are commonly used in the digital porous media community, such as [PoreSpy](https://porespy.org), [scikit-image](https://scikit-image.org/), and [PyVista](https://docs.pyvista.org/). \n",
    "\n",
    "Further, our intent is for these tools to be used with the [Digital Porous Media Portal](https://digitalporousmedia.org) (**DPMP**, formerly Digital Rocks Portal), an excellent source of data! The Portal has undergone significant redesign, and part of the transition includes integration of these tools in dedicated virtual machines and on high-performance computing resources with direct access to Portal data. We invite you to check out the [DPMP Documentation](https://digitalporousmedia.org/how-to-use/) for more details.\n",
    "\n",
    "## **Prerequisites**\n",
    "Most of the tools available in this library are designed to work with 2D and 3D [Numpy](https://numpy.org) arrays. We have also implemented an ``Image`` dataclass that contains additional information to streamline integration with the Digital Porous Media Portal. This dataclass is also used for the 3D visualization module.\n",
    "\n",
    "## **Quick Start Guide**"
   ]
  },

    "import dpm_tools as dpm\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import skimage"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "64c92ec9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Reading Images\n",
    "\n",
    "As part of our ``io`` module, we currently have a wrapper function to read 2D and 3D images from various file formats that are present on DPMP. However, most functions can be used with any 2D or 3D Numpy array."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "1582fbb4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 500x500 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "path = \"../data/berea_pore.tif\"\n",
    "\n",
    "berea_pore = dpm.io.read_image(path)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=[5, 5])\n",
    "img = ax.imshow(berea_pore[50], cmap=\"gray\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1454f61e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Segmentation\n",
    "The DPM Tools ``segmentation`` module currently includes two segmentation algorithms: Statistical Region Merging (SRM) and Seeded Region Growing (SRG). \n",
    "\n",
    "These algorithms are implemented in Fiji/ImageJ, but to our knowledge, have not yet been widely distributed in Python. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Statistical Region Merging"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "94af7096",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x500 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "coins_image = skimage.data.coins()\n",
    "segmented = dpm.segmentation.statistical_region_merging(coins_image, Q=5.0)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the result\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 5))\n",
    "ax[0].imshow(coins_image)#[0, :, :])\n",
    "ax[0].set_title(\"Original Image\")\n",
    "ax[1].imshow(segmented)#[0, :, :])\n",
    "ax[1].set_title(\"Segmented Image\")\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f1c518c5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Seeded Region Growing"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "823f07a0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x500 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from scipy.ndimage import binary_fill_holes\n",
    "coins_image = skimage.data.coins()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Seed labels start from 1. SRG fills in 0s\n",
    "coin_seeds = (coins_image > 150).astype(np.uint8) * 2\n",
    "background_seeds = (coins_image < 105).astype(np.uint8)\n",
    "seeds = coin_seeds + background_seeds\n",
    "\n",
    "segmented = dpm.segmentation.seeded_region_growing(coins_image, seeds, normalize=True)\n",
    "# Subtract 1 to make the labels start from 0\n",
    "segmented -= 1\n",
    "segmented = binary_fill_holes(segmented)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Plot the result\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(10, 5))\n",
    "ax[0].imshow(coins_image)\n",
    "ax[0].set_title(\"Original Image\")\n",
    "ax[1].imshow(seeds)\n",
    "ax[1].set_title(\"Seeds\")\n",
    "ax[2].imshow(segmented)\n",
    "ax[2].set_title(\"Segmented Image\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0da5dd6c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Metrics\n",
    "The ``metrics`` module provides various functions for characterizing the geometry of a binarized tomogram. These include both scalar metrics such as the Minkowski functionals and local metrics such as the Euclidean distance transform.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Minkowski Functionals"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "d69c9e1a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Volume: 236764.00 cubic voxels\n",
      "Surface Area: 40608.00 square voxels\n",
      "Integral Mean Curvature: 1824.22 (voxels)\n",
      "Euler Characteristic: 0.00\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "pore_phase = 0\n",
    "berea_pore = berea_pore == pore_phase\n",
    "\n",
    "mfs = dpm.metrics.minkowski_functionals(berea_pore)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Volume: {mfs[0]:.2f} cubic voxels\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Surface Area: {mfs[1]:.2f} square voxels\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Integral Mean Curvature: {mfs[2]:.2f} (voxels)\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Euler Characteristic: {mfs[3]:.2f}\")\n"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "### 3D Visualization\n",
    "The DPM Tools ``visualization`` module contains wrapper functions for interactive 3D visualization using PyVista. These include visualizations of isosurfaces, streamlines, medial axes, and more! \n",
    "\n",
    "***Disclaimer:***\n",
    "\n",
    "Because the VTK wheels on PyPI and Anaconda do not have MPI enabled, parallelism is currently not supported. For larger images, we recommend using dedicated tools such as Paraview."
   ]
  },
